            {"stageId": "s0_smb_preparation", "irPhase": "Preparation", "prompt": 'Six months before the outbreak, your vulnerability scanner identifies MS17-010 (EternalBlue) unpatched on 340 Windows workstations across a flat /16 network. SMBv1 is enabled domain-wide. What is the correct prioritised remediation sequence?', "analystContext": 'MS17-010 CVSS 9.8. Exploit code publicly available since Shadow Brokers leak. No ransomware incidents yet but TI reports worm activity in adjacent sectors. Patch testing cycle normally takes 4 weeks.', "networkContext": 'All workstations on a flat 10.0.0.0/16 network. No internal firewall rules between segments. SMBv1 enabled by GPO for a legacy print application.', "endpointContext": '340 Windows 10 workstations, 12 Windows Server 2012 R2 servers. Patching managed via WSUS. Average patch deployment lag: 28 days.', "irLeadContext": 'CTO asks for a risk-ranked remediation plan. Network re-segmentation is a 6-month project. What do you do NOW?', "options": [{"actionText": 'Deploy MS17-010 patch via emergency WSUS push AND disable SMBv1 via GPO immediately — treat as critical despite testing cycle', "isCorrect": True, "consequence": 'All 340 machines patched within 72 hours. SMBv1 disabled. When the worm variant arrives 6 months later, EternalBlue finds no viable targets.', "nextStageId": 's0_smb_detection', "technicalExplanation": 'MS17-010 CVSS 9.8 with public exploit code warrants emergency patching outside the normal 28-day cycle. Disabling SMBv1 via GPO (Set-SmbServerConfiguration -EnableSMB1Protocol $false) takes effect on next boot and eliminates the attack surface for EternalBlue entirely. Emergency change management processes exist precisely for critical vulnerabilities with active exploitation in the wild.'}, {"actionText": 'Schedule MS17-010 patching through the normal 28-day testing cycle — risk accepted until then', "isCorrect": False, "consequence": 'Worm variant deploys 3 weeks into the patch cycle. 340 unpatched machines fully encrypted before the patch is approved for deployment.', "nextStageId": 's0_smb_detection', "technicalExplanation": 'CVSS 9.8 with public exploit code and active sector exploitation constitutes a critical risk that invalidates normal change management timelines. The 28-day cycle exists for stability — not as an immovable constraint when the alternative is ransomware across 340 machines.'}, {"actionText": 'Block TCP/445 at the perimeter firewall only — internal traffic is trusted', "isCorrect": False, "consequence": 'Perimeter block provides no protection from an insider threat or phishing-delivered payload that executes internally. When EternalBlue runs from an internal machine it reaches all 340 unpatched hosts freely.', "nextStageId": 's0_smb_detection', "technicalExplanation": 'EternalBlue operates east-west on internal networks — perimeter filtering does not constrain internal SMB traffic. On a flat /16 network, a single compromised internal host running EternalBlue can reach all 340 unpatched machines without touching the perimeter firewall.'}, {"actionText": 'Replace the legacy print application first, then disable SMBv1 — estimated 3-month project', "isCorrect": False, "consequence": 'Application replacement takes 4 months. Worm hits at month 2 with SMBv1 still enabled across all 340 machines.', "nextStageId": 's0_smb_detection', "technicalExplanation": 'Application dependency should not delay disabling a critically vulnerable protocol. Interim mitigations (firewall rules isolating the legacy print server, host-based SMBv1 disable on all non-print machines) can be applied immediately while the application migration proceeds in parallel.'}]},
            
            {"stageId": "s0_smb_detection", "irPhase": "Detection & Analysis", "prompt": "Your SIEM fires a high-severity alert: 'Mass SMB connection attempts from single source — potential worm activity'. Source: WS-FINANCE-042, destination: 312 internal IPs on TCP/445, rate: 2,000 connections/minute. EDR shows service 'mssecsvc2.0' created on WS-FINANCE-042. What is your immediate triage action?", "analystContext": 'mssecsvc2.0 is the WannaCry propagation service name — a known IOC. Alert fired 90 seconds ago. DC01 and DC02 not yet showing infection indicators. You have approximately 90 seconds before the DCs are in range.', "networkContext": 'Firewall logs confirm WS-FINANCE-042 scanning the entire /16 subnet on 445/TCP. Broadcast storms developing on floor-3 switch. DNS queries for known WannaCry kill-switch domain observed.', "endpointContext": 'EDR telemetry on WS-FINANCE-042: vssadmin.exe deleting shadow copies, files renamed .wncry, mssecsvc2.0 service registered as SYSTEM.', "irLeadContext": 'This matches WannaCry IOC profile exactly. Declare major incident now or triage further first?', "options": [{"actionText": 'Declare major incident immediately — isolate WS-FINANCE-042, block TCP/445 east-west at internal firewall, escalate to IR team', "isCorrect": True, "consequence": 'mssecsvc2.0 + .wncry extensions + shadow copy deletion = WannaCry confirmed. Major incident declared. Internal 445 blocked. DC isolation prevents domain-wide encryption.', "nextStageId": 's1_emergency', "technicalExplanation": 'Three simultaneous IOCs — known worm service name, ransomware file extensions, shadow copy deletion — constitute confirmed malware execution, not a suspected event. The 90-second window before DC infection means triage and containment must happen in parallel. Declaring a major incident immediately activates the full IR team and authorises emergency network changes.'}, {"actionText": 'Open a ticket and assign to Tier-2 for investigation — wait for their analysis before escalating', "isCorrect": False, "consequence": 'Tier-2 analyst acknowledges the ticket 12 minutes later. DCs infected at minute 3. All 312 machines encrypted by minute 15.', "nextStageId": 's1_emergency', "technicalExplanation": 'Ticket-based workflows are designed for non-urgent events. Three simultaneous confirmed worm IOCs during an active outbreak require immediate escalation and parallel action — not sequential handoff through a queue. The 90-second DC protection window is incompatible with ticketing delays.'}, {"actionText": 'Isolate WS-FINANCE-042 only and monitor whether other machines show the same pattern', "isCorrect": False, "consequence": 'WS-FINANCE-042 isolated but the worm had already propagated to 14 machines before isolation. Those 14 continue spreading. DCs encrypted at minute 5.', "nextStageId": 's1_emergency', "technicalExplanation": 'Isolating patient zero is correct but insufficient when the worm has already propagated. The scan rate of 2,000 connections/minute means EternalBlue exploitation of multiple hosts occurred in the seconds before the SIEM alert fired. Internal firewall rules blocking east-west TCP/445 are required to stop the already-spreading worm.'}, {"actionText": 'Verify the alert is not a false positive by checking the source machine manually via RDP', "isCorrect": False, "consequence": "RDP connection to WS-FINANCE-042 establishes successfully — then your analyst's jump server becomes the 313th infected machine. Alert was real.", "nextStageId": 's1_emergency', "technicalExplanation": 'Connecting to a suspected live ransomware host via RDP exposes the connecting machine to the same worm. Verification should use read-only telemetry (EDR console, SIEM log review, netflow) — never direct connection to a potentially compromised host during an active worm event.'}]},
            
